# CarbonFlow EV

**EV Charging Station Optimization & Carbon Credit Engine**

CarbonFlow EV is a dashboard that helps EV charging station owners understand how much of their energy demand can be met by on-site solar generation instead of the grid — showing the resulting cost savings and the carbon credit revenue that comes with it.

> ⚠️ **Status: Prototype / Demo.** This project currently runs on simulated data (see [Data Sources](#data-sources) below). It is not connected to a live charging station, inverter, or grid meter.

## Live Demo

[carbonflow-ev-513804914430.asia-southeast1.run.app](https://carbonflow-ev-513804914430.asia-southeast1.run.app/)

## The Problem

EV charging stations draw a lot of power, and most of that power still comes from the grid at full tariff rates — even when the station has solar panels installed. Station owners often don't have an easy way to see:

- How much of their EV charging demand solar is actually covering, hour by hour
- How much money that's saving them vs. pure grid power
- How to size their solar + battery setup for their specific usage pattern
- The carbon credit value they're generating by offsetting grid electricity

CarbonFlow EV brings all of this into one view.

## Features

- **Station configuration** — set solar capacity (kW) and battery storage (kWh) via sliders, and pick a customer segment (Tech Park/Commercial, Institution/Hospital, Residential Complex) that applies a realistic tariff and usage profile
- **Solar Generation vs EV Demand** — real-time chart comparing solar output against charging load throughout the day
- **Cost Savings Analysis** — grid cost with vs. without solar, broken down by time-of-day block
- **Battery State of Charge (SOC)** — simulated charge/discharge cycle over 24 hours
- **Carbon Revenue** — estimated carbon credit income based on CO₂ offset from solar usage
- **Recommendations** — simple rule-based suggestions (e.g., increasing battery storage to capture more solar for evening discharge)
- **Projected Annual ROI** — combined view of electricity savings + carbon credit revenue and their impact on breakeven
- **Export Report** — generate a shareable summary of the current configuration and results

## Data Sources

| Data | Source | Status |
|---|---|---|
| Solar irradiance / weather | [NASA POWER API](https://power.larc.nasa.gov/) | Real — pulled for the configured latitude/longitude |
| EV charging demand profile | Synthetic model | Simulated, based on customer segment (e.g., daytime-heavy for Tech Park, overnight for Residential) |
| Grid tariffs | Configured per segment | Illustrative, not live utility rates |
| Battery behavior | Simple charge/discharge simulation | Simulated |
| Carbon credit pricing | Fixed assumption | Illustrative |

Solar generation is grounded in real historical/typical irradiance data for the given location via the NASA POWER API. Everything downstream of that (demand, tariffs, battery cycling, carbon pricing) is currently modeled/simulated rather than pulled from a live station, since no real deployment data is available yet.

## Tech Stack

- **Frontend:** React + TypeScript, Vite
- **Charts:** Custom chart components (`SavingsChart`, `EnergyChart`, `BatteryChart`)
- **Deployment:** Google Cloud Run (`asia-southeast1`)

## Project Structure

```
├── App.tsx
├── constants.tsx
├── types.ts
├── components/
│   ├── Auth.tsx
│   ├── InputSection.tsx
│   ├── MetricsGrid.tsx
│   └── charts/
│       ├── BatteryChart.tsx
│       ├── EnergyChart.tsx
│       └── SavingsChart.tsx
└── services/
    └── engine.ts        # core simulation/calculation logic
```

## Roadmap

- [ ] Connect to real smart meter / inverter APIs (e.g., SolarEdge, Growatt, Huawei) for live solar generation data
- [ ] Integrate with OCPP-compliant charger feeds for real EV charging demand
- [ ] Replace fixed carbon credit pricing with live market rates
- [ ] Add automated tests for the simulation engine
- [ ] Modularize `engine.ts` into separate solar, battery, tariff, and carbon models

## Getting Started

```bash
git clone <repo-url>
cd EVquotient
npm install
npm run dev
```

## Disclaimer

All monetary figures, savings percentages, and carbon offset numbers shown in the live demo are generated from a simulation and customer-segment presets. They are illustrative of the tool's capability, not real station data.
